Chapter 1 Exercises has a look at the effect of clamping or lack thereof on how the network reaches a
resolution. Without the clamp we can see random starting patterns reach one or other of the prototype
patterns, and very often reach neither.
With TAN22 clamped to 0 neither prototype can ever be reached as both use it. Most of the time the
network cycles, sometimes timing out
With TAN22 clamped to 1, the network is much more likely to get to T or H with varying probabilities,
given both use it, occasionally timing out.
Answer 1 declares $1100$$$$ has no generalisation which seemed unlikely. No1 answer below indicates
All-0s for the undefineds will reach T every time, All-1s will reach H 31% of the time, cycling otherwise.
Answer 4 declares 101000010 will reach 111000000 with F22 clamped. My code reports clamping F22 to 0
results in 111000010. Manually working through versus the truth table on page 14 suggests the book
shows the wrong answer.

$ php chap1.exercises.php
